00:15:26.320 --> 00:15:28.195
But I want to make sure
everybody understands

00:15:28.195 --> 00:15:29.910
this basic framework
first, because we're

00:15:29.910 --> 00:15:33.540
going to now start making this
a little bit more complex.

00:15:33.540 --> 00:15:37.290
Where we left off at the very
last moment of Wednesday's

00:15:37.290 --> 00:15:41.219
lecture was I showed
you this diagram

00:15:41.219 --> 00:15:43.260
with the tangency portfolio,
but we hadn't really

00:15:43.260 --> 00:15:44.790
gotten to talking about it.

00:15:44.790 --> 00:15:48.510
Remember the case where we had
only one risky asset and one

00:15:48.510 --> 00:15:50.710
riskless asset, treasury bills?

00:15:50.710 --> 00:15:54.420
And in that case, when you
are combining a portfolio

00:15:54.420 --> 00:15:57.450
with one risky asset
and one riskless,

00:15:57.450 --> 00:15:58.680
you've got a straight line.

00:15:58.680 --> 00:16:01.300
It turns out that that
is much more general.

00:16:01.300 --> 00:16:05.460
You get a straight line anytime
you combine a riskless asset

00:16:05.460 --> 00:16:07.880
with any number of risky assets.

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:09.820
So let me give you an example.

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:12.720
Suppose we picked an
arbitrary portfolio which

00:16:12.720 --> 00:16:14.990
is this red dot, p.

00:16:14.990 --> 00:16:17.180
And I wanted you
to tell me what is

00:16:17.180 --> 00:16:19.400
the risk-reward
possibilities that you

00:16:19.400 --> 00:16:25.204
could achieve by mixing
p with treasury bills.

00:16:25.204 --> 00:16:26.870
Well, you get that
straight line, right?

00:16:26.870 --> 00:16:29.450
We derived that last time.

00:16:29.450 --> 00:16:33.680
So any point along the straight
line is what you could achieve,

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:34.820
right?

00:16:34.820 --> 00:16:37.010
Anybody tell me
where the portfolio

00:16:37.010 --> 00:16:42.890
would be that invests 100%
of your assets in T-Bills?

00:16:42.890 --> 00:16:44.300
Where is that on this graph?

00:16:44.300 --> 00:16:45.650
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:16:45.650 --> 00:16:47.191
ANDREW LO: Right
this dot right here.

00:16:47.191 --> 00:16:49.600
How about 100% in portfolio p?

00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:50.930
Right, the red dot over there.

00:16:50.930 --> 00:16:57.110
How about 25% in
T-Bills, 75% in p?

00:16:57.110 --> 00:16:59.189
Where would that lie?

00:16:59.189 --> 00:17:00.730
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
along the line.

00:17:00.730 --> 00:17:02.771
ANDREW LO: It would be
along the line, but where?

00:17:02.771 --> 00:17:04.770
Here?

00:17:04.770 --> 00:17:07.386
25% T-Bills, 75%--

00:17:07.386 --> 00:17:08.260
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:17:08.260 --> 00:17:09.609
ANDREW LO: Right, exactly.

00:17:09.609 --> 00:17:13.240
It would be 3/4 of the
