00:19:17.124 --> 00:19:18.879
[INAUDIBLE]

00:19:18.879 --> 00:19:19.670
ANDREW LO: Exactly.

00:19:19.670 --> 00:19:21.440
If you picked any
other portfolio

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:24.950
besides the tangency portfolio,
let's pick one and see.

00:19:24.950 --> 00:19:28.070
If you picked, let's
say this one right here.

00:19:28.070 --> 00:19:31.910
If you drew a line between
this point and that portfolio,

00:19:31.910 --> 00:19:33.380
it's going to turn
out that there

00:19:33.380 --> 00:19:36.860
are other points over
here that are strictly

00:19:36.860 --> 00:19:42.850
in the Northwest of that line,
that you could do better.

00:19:42.850 --> 00:19:46.450
There exists only one
portfolio that you

00:19:46.450 --> 00:19:52.930
can mix with T-Bills, such that
you can never, ever do better

00:19:52.930 --> 00:19:56.050
in terms of generating
risk-reward trade-offs

00:19:56.050 --> 00:20:00.670
for everybody that
likes expected return,

00:20:00.670 --> 00:20:01.870
and doesn't like risk.

00:20:01.870 --> 00:20:04.600
And it turns out that
that portfolio happens

00:20:04.600 --> 00:20:08.140
to be the tangency portfolio.

00:20:08.140 --> 00:20:11.350
That's the portfolio that
all of you in this room

00:20:11.350 --> 00:20:12.646
would love to have.

00:20:12.646 --> 00:20:15.270
I don't know anything about you,
I don't know your backgrounds,

00:20:15.270 --> 00:20:16.180
I don't know your
risk aversions,

00:20:16.180 --> 00:20:17.320
but I don't have to know.

00:20:17.320 --> 00:20:20.150
As long as I know that
you like expected return

00:20:20.150 --> 00:20:22.900
and you don't like risk,
those are the only assumptions

00:20:22.900 --> 00:20:23.590
that I need.

00:20:23.590 --> 00:20:26.025
Then I know, all of
you in this room,

00:20:26.025 --> 00:20:27.400
are going to want
that portfolio.

00:20:27.400 --> 00:20:30.550
You may not be at
that portfolio.

00:20:30.550 --> 00:20:32.650
For example, some of
you who don't like risk,

00:20:32.650 --> 00:20:34.860
you're going to be down here.

00:20:34.860 --> 00:20:37.500
Those of you who are
budding hedge fund managers,

00:20:37.500 --> 00:20:40.390
you're going to be up here.

00:20:40.390 --> 00:20:42.710
But the point is, you're
going to be on this line.

00:20:42.710 --> 00:20:45.170
You're not going to be
on this line down here.

00:20:45.170 --> 00:20:45.670
Why?

00:20:45.670 --> 00:20:49.510
Because why be on that line
when you could get higher return

00:20:49.510 --> 00:20:51.700
for a given level of
risk, or a lower risk

00:20:51.700 --> 00:20:53.400
for a given level of return.

00:20:53.400 --> 00:20:55.570
You're giving up something
for no good reason.

00:20:59.660 --> 00:21:03.400
So this is a remarkable insight
of modern portfolio theory.

00:21:03.400 --> 00:21:06.610
This basically tells
us that regardless

00:21:06.610 --> 00:21:09.370
of our differences
in preferences,

00:21:09.370 --> 00:21:11.590
as long as we satisfy
the hypothesis

00:21:11.590 --> 00:21:14.770
that we like expected return
and we don't like risk, that

00:21:14.770 --> 00:21:16.450
means that everybody
in this room

00:21:16.450 --> 00:21:19.480
will agree that the only line
that they would ever want

00:21:19.480 --> 00:21:23.020
to be on is that tangency line.

