00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:01.740
The slope, that's right.

00:25:01.740 --> 00:25:06.545
You're going to get more
expected return per unit risk.

00:25:06.545 --> 00:25:07.920
And that is
something we're going

00:25:07.920 --> 00:25:12.870
to take as a measure of how good
this particular trade-off is.

00:25:12.870 --> 00:25:16.120
We're going to look at
that slope of this line.

00:25:16.120 --> 00:25:17.970
And the slope of this
line will give us

00:25:17.970 --> 00:25:23.340
a measure of the expected
rate of return per unit risk.

00:25:23.340 --> 00:25:25.874
That's exactly what
it's going to do for us.

00:25:25.874 --> 00:25:27.762
AUDIENCE: So if you're
in the upper right

00:25:27.762 --> 00:25:30.440
beyond the tangency
[INAUDIBLE], you know that line?

00:25:30.440 --> 00:25:32.940
Then you're borrowing
[INAUDIBLE] portfolio?

00:25:32.940 --> 00:25:34.420
ANDREW LO: That's correct.

00:25:34.420 --> 00:25:37.088
AUDIENCE: If you were to
extend the line leftwards, down

00:25:37.088 --> 00:25:39.171
to the left, would you be
then shorting the market

00:25:39.171 --> 00:25:40.047
to invest in T-Bills?

00:25:40.047 --> 00:25:40.671
ANDREW LO: Yes.

00:25:40.671 --> 00:25:42.710
And if that happens, you
know what you would do?

00:25:42.710 --> 00:25:44.970
It would not go this
way, because of course

00:25:44.970 --> 00:25:46.860
standard deviation
can't be negative.

00:25:46.860 --> 00:25:47.950
It would go like this.

00:25:47.950 --> 00:25:49.680
It would go this way.

00:25:49.680 --> 00:25:51.809
Because standard deviation
is always non-negative.

00:25:51.809 --> 00:25:53.350
It's the square root
of the variance,

00:25:53.350 --> 00:25:54.670
which is always positive.

00:25:54.670 --> 00:25:58.290
So if you decided to short
the tangency portfolio

00:25:58.290 --> 00:26:03.540
and put it in T-Bills, well,
you'd be a knucklehead.

00:26:03.540 --> 00:26:06.360
But you would be on
this line right here.

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:09.270
You would have higher and
higher risk, because you're

00:26:09.270 --> 00:26:11.790
taking a short
position on equities,

00:26:11.790 --> 00:26:13.470
and you'd have a
lower and lower return

00:26:13.470 --> 00:26:15.303
because you're shorting
the high yield asset

00:26:15.303 --> 00:26:16.680
and buying the low yield asset.

00:26:22.010 --> 00:26:25.690
Any other questions about
the geometry of this point.

00:26:25.690 --> 00:26:28.770
It's very important,
this is a major insight.

00:26:28.770 --> 00:26:29.664
Yeah?

00:26:29.664 --> 00:26:31.330
AUDIENCE: Earlier we
discussed about how

00:26:31.330 --> 00:26:34.676
we bring market [INAUDIBLE]
portfolios and expected return

00:26:34.676 --> 00:26:37.384
changes as a function of
n and standard deviation

00:26:37.384 --> 00:26:39.950
from certain changes [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:39.950 --> 00:26:40.778
ANDREW LO: Yes.

00:26:40.778 --> 00:26:43.560
AUDIENCE: Is that the reason why
the shift is more towards left?

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:46.410
Because as we add more
and more portfolios,

00:26:46.410 --> 00:26:47.940
the n dominates the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:26:47.940 --> 00:26:49.523
ANDREW LO: That's
right, that's right.

00:26:49.523 --> 00:26:52.560
As we add more securities,
you get more and more impact

00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:54.550
of diversification.

00:26:54.550 --> 00:26:58.950
So that increases your expected
rate of return per unit risk

00:26:58.950 --> 00:27:01.110
because you can't make
somebody worse off

00:27:01.110 --> 00:27:03.000
by giving them choices.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:05.610
They can always put a
0 for the new stocks

00:27:05.610 --> 00:27:07.690
that you give them if
they don't like it.

00:27:07.690 --> 00:27:11.070
So the only thing you can do is
to make you better off, meaning

00:27:11.070 --> 00:27:12.930
the only thing you
can do is to give you

00:27:12.930 --> 00:27:15.750
a higher level of expected
return per unit risk,

00:27:15.750 --> 00:27:19.560
or a lower level of risk
per unit of expected return.

00:27:19.560 --> 00:27:21.870
So by adding more
securities, you're

00:27:21.870 --> 00:27:26.290
basically increasing
the slope of this line.

00:27:26.290 --> 00:27:28.840
So let's talk about
the slope of the line.

00:27:28.840 --> 00:27:33.450
The slope of that line is
equal to the expected return

00:27:33.450 --> 00:27:38.010
of that tangency portfolio,
minus the T-Bill rate, divided

00:27:38.010 --> 00:27:41.460
by the volatility of
that tangency portfolio.

00:27:41.460 --> 00:27:43.890
If you just calculate
rise over run,

00:27:43.890 --> 00:27:45.990
that's what you
get as the slope.

00:27:45.990 --> 00:27:47.370
There's a name for this.

00:27:47.370 --> 00:27:49.290
The name for this is
called the Sharpe ratio.

00:27:49.290 --> 00:27:50.970
You may have heard
of this, particularly

00:27:50.970 --> 00:27:53.620
those of you who have interest
in hedge fund investments.

00:27:53.620 --> 00:27:56.700
Hedge fund managers will often
quote their Sharpe ratio very

00:27:56.700 --> 00:27:57.930
proudly.

00:27:57.930 --> 00:28:00.330
The Sharpe ratio
is simply a measure

00:28:00.330 --> 00:28:01.950
of that risk-reward trade-off.

00:28:01.950 --> 00:28:05.950
The higher the Sharpe ratio,
the better you're doing.

00:28:05.950 --> 00:28:10.070
If you're a mean variance
optimizer, meaning you

00:28:10.070 --> 00:28:14.440
prefer more expected
return and less risk.

00:28:17.510 --> 00:28:20.720
So the idea behind
the tangency portfolio

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:22.610
is that it is the one
that will give you

00:28:22.610 --> 00:28:24.320
the highest Sharpe ratio.

00:28:24.320 --> 00:28:25.760
Let's look at it again.

00:28:25.760 --> 00:28:28.820
If you pick a portfolio
like here, take a look.

00:28:28.820 --> 00:28:29.730
Look at the slope.

00:28:29.730 --> 00:28:32.060
The slope is going to be lower.

00:28:32.060 --> 00:28:35.750
Take a point over here,
in the inefficient branch

00:28:35.750 --> 00:28:36.740
of the bullet.

00:28:36.740 --> 00:28:38.300
Then the slope is
going to be even

00:28:38.300 --> 00:28:40.250
lower than the upper branch.

00:28:40.250 --> 00:28:47.330
The biggest slope occurs when
you invest between T-Bills

00:28:47.330 --> 00:28:50.370
and that tangency portfolio.

00:28:50.370 --> 00:28:54.282
That's what you're optimizing.

00:28:54.282 --> 00:28:55.746
Yeah?

00:28:55.746 --> 00:28:58.674
AUDIENCE: I have a
hard time understanding

00:28:58.674 --> 00:29:03.570
why the bullet would go left
when I add additional stocks.

00:29:03.570 --> 00:29:07.300
I understand it analytically,
standard deviation goes down.

00:29:07.300 --> 00:29:11.499
But then on the other
hand, wouldn't it

00:29:11.499 --> 00:29:16.030
happen that the
likelihood of correlation

00:29:16.030 --> 00:29:19.509
between these
additional stocks would

00:29:19.509 --> 00:29:22.765
decrease and therefore as we--

00:29:22.765 --> 00:29:24.640
ANDREW LO: How would
the correlation increase

00:29:24.640 --> 00:29:25.870
by adding another stock?

00:29:25.870 --> 00:29:30.160
AUDIENCE: I mean the likelihood
that I have 20 stocks,

00:29:30.160 --> 00:29:35.312
the overall correlation is
higher rather than [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:35.312 --> 00:29:36.520
ANDREW LO: How could that be?

00:29:36.520 --> 00:29:39.310
You've got 20
stocks, and they've

00:29:39.310 --> 00:29:42.470
got a correlation
among those 20 stocks.

00:29:42.470 --> 00:29:46.730
Now, I want you to think
about adding a 21st stock.

00:29:46.730 --> 00:29:48.980
When you add that
21st stock, you

00:29:48.980 --> 00:29:51.380
don't affect the existing
correlations, right?

00:29:51.380 --> 00:29:53.540
I mean, it is whatever it is.

00:29:53.540 --> 00:29:54.950
Those are parameters.

00:29:54.950 --> 00:29:57.790
At least for now, we're going
to call them parameters.

00:29:57.790 --> 00:30:02.330
When I add my 21st stock,
I'm giving the investor

00:30:02.330 --> 00:30:03.840
an extra degree of freedom.

00:30:03.840 --> 00:30:07.460
Now instead of investing
among 20 securities,

00:30:07.460 --> 00:30:09.140
I'm going to let
you invest among 21.

00:30:09.140 --> 00:30:11.772
You don't have to
invest in the 21st.

00:30:11.772 --> 00:30:13.230
Or another way of
thinking about it

00:30:13.230 --> 00:30:16.590
is that when you
only had 20 stocks,

00:30:16.590 --> 00:30:19.710
you really had 21
portfolio weights.

00:30:19.710 --> 00:30:21.870
But the 21st weight,
I've arbitrarily

00:30:21.870 --> 00:30:24.320
constrained to be 0.

00:30:24.320 --> 00:30:26.630
Now, I'm going to
loosen the constraint

00:30:26.630 --> 00:30:28.070
and I'm going to
say, OK, now you

00:30:28.070 --> 00:30:31.390
can invest in the 21st stock.

00:30:31.390 --> 00:30:33.340
You won't affect the
existing correlations,

00:30:33.340 --> 00:30:34.900
but the new stock
that you add in

00:30:34.900 --> 00:30:39.320
can benefit in providing
additional diversification

00:30:39.320 --> 00:30:39.820
benefits.

00:30:39.820 --> 00:30:41.507
AUDIENCE: But as a
general rule, we've

00:30:41.507 --> 00:30:45.467
always been trying to have
negative correlation so

00:30:45.467 --> 00:30:46.515
that the bullet was left.

00:30:46.515 --> 00:30:47.890
ANDREW LO: Oh,
well actually, you

00:30:47.890 --> 00:30:49.210
don't need a
negative correlation

00:30:49.210 --> 00:30:50.751
to make this go to
the left, you just

00:30:50.751 --> 00:30:53.540
need to have
something less than 1.

00:30:53.540 --> 00:30:54.200
Remember?

00:30:54.200 --> 00:30:55.440
From the last lecture?

00:30:55.440 --> 00:30:59.000
This is a case where you
had perfect correlation.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.850
Anything less than
perfect correlation,

00:31:01.850 --> 00:31:04.850
brings you to the left.

00:31:04.850 --> 00:31:08.180
So as long as my
21st stock is not

00:31:08.180 --> 00:31:10.670
perfectly correlated
with the existing

00:31:10.670 --> 00:31:13.400
stocks in that
portfolio of 20, I'm

00:31:13.400 --> 00:31:14.894
going to move
things to the left.

00:31:14.894 --> 00:31:17.190
AUDIENCE: In general,
[INAUDIBLE] any stocks?

00:31:17.190 --> 00:31:18.690
ANDREW LO: In
general, that is true.

00:31:18.690 --> 00:31:22.440
AUDIENCE: I mean I would try to
have the negative correlation.

00:31:22.440 --> 00:31:24.690
ANDREW LO: You would,
but what this suggests

00:31:24.690 --> 00:31:26.820
is that negative correlation
is a very rare thing.

00:31:26.820 --> 00:31:27.690
AUDIENCE: It's difficult.

00:31:27.690 --> 00:31:30.064
ANDREW LO: It's very difficult,
it's extremely difficult.

00:31:30.064 --> 00:31:32.760
Now, from the
analytical perspective,

00:31:32.760 --> 00:31:34.260
we can conclude
it's very difficult.

00:31:34.260 --> 00:31:37.440
Let me ask you from an
economic perspective,

00:31:37.440 --> 00:31:40.680
why is it difficult to find
a stock that's negatively

00:31:40.680 --> 00:31:42.540
correlated with
all other stocks?

00:31:42.540 --> 00:31:46.350
Anybody give me a business
rationale for that?

00:31:46.350 --> 00:31:47.502
Yeah, Ingrid?

00:31:47.502 --> 00:31:49.150
AUDIENCE: There's
what you said before

00:31:49.150 --> 00:31:52.004
that when the economy goes
