00:35:10.724 --> 00:35:12.390
The bottom line is
that it's really hard

00:35:12.390 --> 00:35:14.832
to come up with negative
correlated stocks.

00:35:14.832 --> 00:35:17.040
Let me tell you, if you
found one that was negatively

00:35:17.040 --> 00:35:20.490
correlated, if you found
one that was really, really,

00:35:20.490 --> 00:35:23.112
negatively correlated,
what would all of you do?

00:35:23.112 --> 00:35:23.820
AUDIENCE: Buy it.

00:35:23.820 --> 00:35:26.310
ANDREW LO: Exactly,
you'd buy it.

00:35:26.310 --> 00:35:30.210
The effect of that would
be to increase the price

00:35:30.210 --> 00:35:33.570
and depress the expected return.

00:35:33.570 --> 00:35:35.160
Remember what the
expected return is.

00:35:35.160 --> 00:35:39.270
It's the expected future price,
divided by the current price.

00:35:39.270 --> 00:35:42.150
If now all of you go
out and buy Wal-Mart,

00:35:42.150 --> 00:35:44.900
or whatever stock you think
is negatively correlated,

00:35:44.900 --> 00:35:48.990
that would have the impact of
increasing the current price

00:35:48.990 --> 00:35:52.164
and therefore decreasing
the expected return.

00:35:52.164 --> 00:35:53.580
Now if you have a
stock that's got

00:35:53.580 --> 00:35:56.821
a negative covariance
and a negative return,

00:35:56.821 --> 00:35:57.570
that doesn't help.

00:35:57.570 --> 00:35:59.340
Because in fact,
that was a suggestion

00:35:59.340 --> 00:36:00.660
that was put forward here.

00:36:00.660 --> 00:36:03.960
Let's just take the
S&amp;P and short it,

00:36:03.960 --> 00:36:06.280
and then you get a
negatively correlated stock.

00:36:06.280 --> 00:36:09.000
The problem is that it's also
got a negative expected return

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:11.306
and then you're
not helping things.

00:36:11.306 --> 00:36:12.930
The key is to find
negative correlation

00:36:12.930 --> 00:36:14.100
with a positive return.

00:36:14.100 --> 00:36:16.410
If you can find
that, then you've

00:36:16.410 --> 00:36:19.110
really found
something worthwhile.

00:36:19.110 --> 00:36:22.830
But my guess is it won't
last, for exactly this reason.

00:36:22.830 --> 00:36:24.420
Other questions?

00:36:24.420 --> 00:36:27.650
OK, so now, let's go back
and ask the question, what

00:36:27.650 --> 00:36:30.920
does this mean if we
agree that all of us

00:36:30.920 --> 00:36:33.920
want to be on that
tangency portfolio.

00:36:33.920 --> 00:36:35.940
What does that tell us?

00:36:35.940 --> 00:36:41.250
Well, that allows us to
then make an argument

00:36:41.250 --> 00:36:46.170
that managers that are
trying to provide value

00:36:46.170 --> 00:36:51.560
added services for us, they
need to be doing something above

00:36:51.560 --> 00:36:55.700
and beyond what we
can do ourselves.

00:36:55.700 --> 00:36:58.280
Now, here's where Warren Buffett
meets modern finance theory,

00:36:58.280 --> 00:37:01.090
in a way.

00:37:01.090 --> 00:37:02.740
If I want to see
whether or not Warren

00:37:02.740 --> 00:37:05.290
Buffett or any other
managers are adding value,

00:37:05.290 --> 00:37:08.990
one simple criterion that
I can put forward is this.

00:37:08.990 --> 00:37:10.960
This Is what I can do on my own.

00:37:10.960 --> 00:37:16.240
I can get that line pretty much
by just using my basic finance

00:37:16.240 --> 00:37:19.670
skills that I've
learned here at MIT.

00:37:19.670 --> 00:37:23.570
If you're going to manage my
money and charge me 2 and 20,

00:37:23.570 --> 00:37:26.420
show me what you can do
above and beyond this.

00:37:26.420 --> 00:37:29.720
I want you to tell me where
you can get me on this graph.

00:37:29.720 --> 00:37:32.870
Can you get me up here?

00:37:32.870 --> 00:37:34.540
Can you get me over here?

00:37:34.540 --> 00:37:37.690
Can you get me anywhere
either to the left

00:37:37.690 --> 00:37:40.850
or above that curve?

00:37:40.850 --> 00:37:43.650
We can use that as a
measure of performance,

00:37:43.650 --> 00:37:45.680
and there's a name for that.

00:37:45.680 --> 00:37:46.910
It's called Alpha.

00:37:46.910 --> 00:37:48.980
Typically, when people
talk about Alpha,

00:37:48.980 --> 00:37:52.022
they're talking about deviations
from a line like this.

00:37:52.022 --> 00:37:53.730
We're going to get to
that more formally,

00:37:53.730 --> 00:37:56.230
you don't have to write it down
or make note of it just yet.

00:37:56.230 --> 00:37:57.544
It's on the next slide.

00:37:57.544 --> 00:37:59.960
But we're going to show you
how to measure that explicitly

00:37:59.960 --> 00:38:04.460
so now, not only is this a
good idea for you as a baseline

00:38:04.460 --> 00:38:07.310
to manage your own
portfolio, but you can then

00:38:07.310 --> 00:38:09.650
use it as a metric to gauge
whether other people are

00:38:09.650 --> 00:38:11.220
adding value to you.

00:38:11.220 --> 00:38:14.780
So Warren Buffett
would say, no problem.

00:38:14.780 --> 00:38:16.310
I think I've got Alpha.

00:38:16.310 --> 00:38:18.110
So I'm not going to
bother with this,

00:38:18.110 --> 00:38:20.710
I think I can get you up here.

00:38:20.710 --> 00:38:23.320
That is, if you want
to invest with me.

00:38:23.320 --> 00:38:26.380
And in fact, if you looked at
Warren Buffett's performance

00:38:26.380 --> 00:38:30.310
over the last 25 years that
he's been doing it, or 30 years,

00:38:30.310 --> 00:38:36.250
his Sharpe ratio is a lot better
than the tangency portfolios.

00:38:36.250 --> 00:38:40.420
So he actually has added value
if you use this as a criterion.

00:38:40.420 --> 00:38:43.780
But the problem is, you
have to identify the Warren

00:38:43.780 --> 00:38:46.171
Buffetts before they
become Warren Buffetts.

00:38:46.171 --> 00:38:47.920
Because after they
become Warren Buffetts,

00:38:47.920 --> 00:38:49.030
it's not clear
that they're adding

00:38:49.030 --> 00:38:50.350
the same amount of value.

00:38:50.350 --> 00:38:52.490
It's already, the
cat's out of the bag.

00:38:52.490 --> 00:38:54.028
Yeah, [INAUDIBLE]?

