00:40:14.162 --> 00:40:16.120
AUDIENCE: You take a
function for the industry?

00:40:16.120 --> 00:40:17.020
ANDREW LO: Yes, yes.

00:40:17.020 --> 00:40:19.450
Now, we haven't talked
about utility functions yet,

00:40:19.450 --> 00:40:21.380
but we're going to
in a little while.

00:40:21.380 --> 00:40:24.790
Let me preview that,
since you asked.

00:40:24.790 --> 00:40:27.370
You all remember what
indifference curves are?

00:40:27.370 --> 00:40:29.380
From basic economics?

00:40:29.380 --> 00:40:32.110
An indifference curve, when
I first came across that,

00:40:32.110 --> 00:40:36.070
I was rather offended
because I don't view myself

00:40:36.070 --> 00:40:37.990
as an indifferent individual.

00:40:37.990 --> 00:40:39.820
I have lots of passions.

00:40:39.820 --> 00:40:43.666
And so, why should we be
indifferent about two choices?

00:40:43.666 --> 00:40:45.040
In fact, that's
an economic term.

00:40:45.040 --> 00:40:49.000
It simply means that you are
just as well off between two

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:51.430
combinations and
therefore, these two

00:40:51.430 --> 00:40:55.600
combinations you're indifferent
to, you're indifferent between.

00:40:55.600 --> 00:41:01.690
So if I had to ask you to draw
on this graph, an indifference

00:41:01.690 --> 00:41:06.501
curve of risk-reward
trade-offs for you,

00:41:06.501 --> 00:41:08.500
the typical individual,
what would it look like?

00:41:08.500 --> 00:41:11.650
Can anybody give me a sense
of what different kinds

00:41:11.650 --> 00:41:15.880
of risk-reward trade-offs you
would be indifferent among?

00:41:15.880 --> 00:41:18.790
And to make the question
a little bit simpler,

00:41:18.790 --> 00:41:20.890
let's start off with
a particular point.

00:41:20.890 --> 00:41:22.780
So let's suppose that
this point right here

00:41:22.780 --> 00:41:25.450
is the point that I want
you to draw the indifferent

00:41:25.450 --> 00:41:27.610
curve from.

00:41:27.610 --> 00:41:31.570
Which is a standard deviation
on a monthly basis of about 6%,

00:41:31.570 --> 00:41:38.180
and an expected return of
about, say 1.4% or something.

00:41:38.180 --> 00:41:45.780
So you've got a monthly return
of 1.4% and a risk of about 6%.

00:41:45.780 --> 00:41:50.760
Give me another point that you
would be indifferent between,

00:41:50.760 --> 00:41:51.560
versus that one?

00:41:56.140 --> 00:41:56.640
Anybody?

00:41:56.640 --> 00:41:57.480
Any volunteers?

00:42:00.917 --> 00:42:01.899
Yeah?

00:42:01.899 --> 00:42:06.640
AUDIENCE: There could be a
point above the tangent line,

00:42:06.640 --> 00:42:07.607
but to your right.

00:42:07.607 --> 00:42:08.940
Somewhere where you're pointing.

00:42:08.940 --> 00:42:11.580
ANDREW LO: OK, so do you have
a particular number in mind?

00:42:11.580 --> 00:42:13.760
In other words, let
me ask you this.

00:42:13.760 --> 00:42:18.524
If I cranked up your
volatility from 6% to 8%,

00:42:18.524 --> 00:42:19.940
how much extra
return would I have

00:42:19.940 --> 00:42:21.898
to give you in order for
you to be just as well

00:42:21.898 --> 00:42:26.299
off as you were at 6% and 1.4%?

00:42:26.299 --> 00:42:28.340
AUDIENCE: Something slightly
higher than the 1.8%

00:42:28.340 --> 00:42:29.720
[INAUDIBLE].

00:42:29.720 --> 00:42:32.430
ANDREW LO: OK,
higher than 1.8% OK.

00:42:32.430 --> 00:42:35.353
AUDIENCE: Or what about
the corresponding value.

00:42:35.353 --> 00:42:35.853
1.41%.

00:42:35.853 --> 00:42:38.790
1.41%

00:42:38.790 --> 00:42:40.940
ANDREW LO: OK, this is 1.41%.

00:42:40.940 --> 00:42:43.670
And if I said, now
I want to be at 8%,

00:42:43.670 --> 00:42:45.171
how much risk do I
have to give you,

00:42:45.171 --> 00:42:47.586
how much expected return do I
have to give you to make you

00:42:47.586 --> 00:42:49.180
just as well off as this point?

00:42:52.180 --> 00:42:54.390
AUDIENCE: Higher
then 1.2%, right?

00:42:54.390 --> 00:42:56.097
Or 1.4%, higher than 1.4%.

00:42:56.097 --> 00:42:57.680
ANDREW LO: Right,
but how much higher?

00:42:57.680 --> 00:42:58.513
That's the question.

00:42:58.513 --> 00:42:59.701
It's a personal question.

00:42:59.701 --> 00:43:00.200
Rami?

00:43:00.200 --> 00:43:05.190
AUDIENCE: 1.3 times your
initial expected return.

00:43:05.190 --> 00:43:06.746
So 33% on top.

00:43:06.746 --> 00:43:08.120
ANDREW LO: You
would have to have

00:43:08.120 --> 00:43:11.150
an increase in 33% of
your expected return,

00:43:11.150 --> 00:43:15.134
even though I'm only giving
you a 25% increase in the risk.

00:43:15.134 --> 00:43:16.118
AUDIENCE: Well, no.

00:43:16.118 --> 00:43:19.316
You'd have to at least
do 25% of the-- sorry.

00:43:19.316 --> 00:43:20.494
Put 6%-8% is--

00:43:20.494 --> 00:43:22.160
ANDREW LO: That's a
third, you're right.

00:43:22.160 --> 00:43:23.990
So I'm increasing
the risk by 1/3,

00:43:23.990 --> 00:43:26.510
you want me to increase
the expected return by 1/3.

00:43:26.510 --> 00:43:28.580
So your trade-off is
linear, is that right?

00:43:28.580 --> 00:43:31.040
You're looking at it linearly?

00:43:31.040 --> 00:43:32.404
Anybody else?

00:43:32.404 --> 00:43:34.070
You know, you may
want to translate this

00:43:34.070 --> 00:43:35.630
into annual numbers.

00:43:35.630 --> 00:43:38.480
Because I'm sensing that
you may not have a good

00:43:38.480 --> 00:43:40.520
feel for what your
own preferences are.

00:43:40.520 --> 00:43:42.260
And by the way,
this is a challenge.

00:43:42.260 --> 00:43:46.370
Not everybody understands what
their own personal preferences

00:43:46.370 --> 00:43:47.970
are for these numbers.

00:43:47.970 --> 00:43:51.230
This is not a natural
act of human nature,

00:43:51.230 --> 00:43:55.670
that we automatically have
preferences on these numbers.

00:43:55.670 --> 00:43:59.770
But the bottom line is that
if I make you take more risk,

00:43:59.770 --> 00:44:02.020
I'm going to have to
compensate you and give you

00:44:02.020 --> 00:44:02.960
more expected return.

00:44:02.960 --> 00:44:05.980
There's got to be a reason why
you want to take that risk.

00:44:05.980 --> 00:44:08.486
For some people, it's linear.

00:44:08.486 --> 00:44:10.360
For other people, it's
much more than linear.

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:11.943
They don't want to
take any more risk.

00:44:11.943 --> 00:44:14.140
In fact, right
now most investors

00:44:14.140 --> 00:44:16.320
don't even want to
answer that question.

00:44:16.320 --> 00:44:18.070
Because they don't
want to take more risk.

00:44:18.070 --> 00:44:19.160
And you say, well
what if you did?

00:44:19.160 --> 00:44:20.210
Well I don't want to.

00:44:20.210 --> 00:44:21.330
Well, but just what if?

00:44:21.330 --> 00:44:22.330
I don't want to what if.

00:44:22.330 --> 00:44:24.460
I just don't want
to take the risk.

00:44:24.460 --> 00:44:26.290
So they can't even
answer that question.

00:44:26.290 --> 00:44:29.450
But if they could, my guess is
that it would be way up here.

00:44:29.450 --> 00:44:31.960
So you'd have to give them
a lot of expected return

00:44:31.960 --> 00:44:34.360
to make people take
more risk today.

00:44:34.360 --> 00:44:37.480
Alternatively, if you want
to give people less risk,

00:44:37.480 --> 00:44:39.040
my guess is that
you can actually

00:44:39.040 --> 00:44:42.610
subtract a lot of return
in order to take away

00:44:42.610 --> 00:44:43.640
a little bit of risk.

00:44:43.640 --> 00:44:44.620
How do I know that?

00:44:44.620 --> 00:44:46.828
Take a look at the yield on
the three month treasury.

00:44:50.420 --> 00:44:53.370
So an indifference curve.

00:44:53.370 --> 00:44:54.730
It's going to look like this.

00:44:54.730 --> 00:44:58.530
It's going to look like
it'll be increasing,

00:44:58.530 --> 00:45:01.680
but it'll actually
be bowed this way.

00:45:01.680 --> 00:45:04.940
And the theory behind why
it's going to be convex,

00:45:04.940 --> 00:45:07.240
holds water as opposed
to spills water,

00:45:07.240 --> 00:45:08.880
the reason it's
going to be convex

00:45:08.880 --> 00:45:12.000
is because there is a
decreasing, or diminishing,

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:15.600
marginal utility between risk
and expected rate of return.

00:45:15.600 --> 00:45:18.420
Like anything else,
economists have this notion

00:45:18.420 --> 00:45:22.320
of diminishing marginal utility
between any two commodities.

00:45:22.320 --> 00:45:29.040
If you've got ice cream
sundaes and basketballs,

00:45:29.040 --> 00:45:30.750
there's only so many
basketballs that you

00:45:30.750 --> 00:45:34.380
can enjoy before the next
incremental basketball provides

00:45:34.380 --> 00:45:36.240
relatively little
pleasure for you.

00:45:36.240 --> 00:45:37.890
The same thing with
ice cream sundaes.

00:45:37.890 --> 00:45:39.870
You can only consume so
many ice cream sundaes

00:45:39.870 --> 00:45:42.990
before the next
incremental sundae provides

00:45:42.990 --> 00:45:45.840
somewhat less benefit to you.

00:45:45.840 --> 00:45:48.480
That kind of diminishing
marginal utility

00:45:48.480 --> 00:45:50.700
gives you this kind
of a bowed curve.

00:45:50.700 --> 00:45:53.250
So where you are on
this straight line

00:45:53.250 --> 00:45:56.070
depends upon how
bowed your curve is.

00:45:56.070 --> 00:45:59.430
Somebody that's really
risk-averse has a curve that

00:45:59.430 --> 00:45:59.930
looks--

00:45:59.930 --> 00:46:01.971
let me draw this because
it's a little bit easier

00:46:01.971 --> 00:46:04.230
to see rather than trying
to follow my laser pointer.

00:46:07.890 --> 00:46:10.650
So here's the trade-off,
this is the line.

00:46:10.650 --> 00:46:12.570
Somebody that's
extremely risk-averse

00:46:12.570 --> 00:46:14.355
is going to have
curves like this.

00:46:17.500 --> 00:46:19.310
Those are indifference curves.

00:46:19.310 --> 00:46:23.640
And as you go to the Northwest,
you're happier and happier.

00:46:23.640 --> 00:46:28.140
So the optimal point is
where this indifference curve

00:46:28.140 --> 00:46:31.970
hits this particular line.

00:46:31.970 --> 00:46:34.970
On the other hand, if
you're very risk-seeking,

00:46:34.970 --> 00:46:36.980
if you don't need a
lot of compensation

00:46:36.980 --> 00:46:39.205
of expected return
per unit risk,

00:46:39.205 --> 00:46:41.580
then your difference curve's
not going to look like that.

00:46:41.580 --> 00:46:45.420
It's going to look like this.

00:46:45.420 --> 00:46:50.970
In which case, you're
tangency point will be farther

00:46:50.970 --> 00:46:53.620
to the Northeast.

00:46:53.620 --> 00:46:55.600
You'll be taking
more risk and getting

00:46:55.600 --> 00:46:58.630
more expected rates of return.

00:46:58.630 --> 00:47:01.180
But the bottom line for
this graph and this lecture

00:47:01.180 --> 00:47:05.395
is that everybody, no matter
what your risk preferences are,

00:47:05.395 --> 00:47:07.270
everybody's going to
want to be on that line,

00:47:07.270 --> 00:47:09.570
that tangency line.

00:47:09.570 --> 00:47:12.020
And it turns out
that that insight

00:47:12.020 --> 00:47:16.070
is going to translate into
a remarkable, remarkable

00:47:16.070 --> 00:47:21.140
conclusion about
risk-reward trade-offs.

00:47:21.140 --> 00:47:23.590
So the key points
for this lecture

00:47:23.590 --> 00:47:27.110
are diversification
reduces risk.

00:47:27.110 --> 00:47:29.600
In diversified
portfolios, covariances

00:47:29.600 --> 00:47:31.940
are the most important
characteristics

00:47:31.940 --> 00:47:32.840
of that portfolio.

00:47:32.840 --> 00:47:37.150
It's not the variances,
but the covariances.

00:47:37.150 --> 00:47:39.250
Investors should try
to hold portfolios

00:47:39.250 --> 00:47:41.920
on the efficient frontier,
that upper branch.

00:47:41.920 --> 00:47:45.160
And with the riskless
asset, everybody

00:47:45.160 --> 00:47:48.790
is going to want to be
on the tangency line.

00:47:48.790 --> 00:47:51.715
Those are the major
conclusions from this analysis.

00:47:51.715 --> 00:47:53.590
And you can work all of
this out analytically

00:47:53.590 --> 00:47:56.320
using the mathematics
of optimization theory,

00:47:56.320 --> 00:47:59.080
but in fact, all of this
can be done graphically

00:47:59.080 --> 00:48:00.935
as we have geometrically.

