01:00:18.100 --> 01:00:22.670
Everybody in the
world wants to hold M.

01:00:22.670 --> 01:00:27.344
So, let's make the leap of faith
that everybody does hold M. So

01:00:27.344 --> 01:00:29.510
in other words, now we're
in a world where everybody

01:00:29.510 --> 01:00:33.290
is already mean
variance optimizers,

01:00:33.290 --> 01:00:39.350
and they already hold two
assets in their portfolio.

01:00:39.350 --> 01:00:44.440
The treasury bill asset, and the
mutual fund M. So you hold M,

01:00:44.440 --> 01:00:47.100
you hold M, you hold M,
you hold M, you hold M,

01:00:47.100 --> 01:00:51.490
everybody holds M. We hold
different amounts of it,

01:00:51.490 --> 01:00:53.680
so as a hedge fund
manager, you're

01:00:53.680 --> 01:00:56.170
holding a large amount
of M. In fact, you're

01:00:56.170 --> 01:00:59.350
holding twice as much M
as your wealth allows,

01:00:59.350 --> 01:01:01.582
and you're borrowing
T-Bills to do so.

01:01:01.582 --> 01:01:03.040
Somebody who's very
conservative is

01:01:03.040 --> 01:01:05.140
holding a very tiny
little bit of M.

01:01:05.140 --> 01:01:08.770
Mostly, that person is
invested in T-Bills.

01:01:08.770 --> 01:01:11.410
But the point is that every
single person's portfolio

01:01:11.410 --> 01:01:13.630
you look at, when you
look at their portfolio,

01:01:13.630 --> 01:01:20.940
it's M. If that's true, if
what I just said is true,

01:01:20.940 --> 01:01:24.610
what portfolio
does M have to be?

01:01:24.610 --> 01:01:27.670
There's only one that
it can possibly be.

01:01:27.670 --> 01:01:31.960
And that is the
portfolio of all equities

01:01:31.960 --> 01:01:36.530
in the marketplace, held in
proportion to their market

01:01:36.530 --> 01:01:38.410
value.

01:01:38.410 --> 01:01:40.570
Do you see the beauty of that?

01:01:40.570 --> 01:01:42.520
Now, let me try to explain it.

01:01:42.520 --> 01:01:45.220
I hope you understand
it, let me explain it.

01:01:45.220 --> 01:01:47.050
Why does that have to be?

01:01:47.050 --> 01:01:48.970
This has to do with
supply equaling demand.

01:01:48.970 --> 01:01:51.460
Now, I'm going to make an
argument about equilibrium.

01:01:51.460 --> 01:01:53.369
I haven't done so up until now.

01:01:53.369 --> 01:01:54.910
Up until now, I
haven't said anything

01:01:54.910 --> 01:01:59.540
about supply equaling demand,
but I'm about to do so.

01:01:59.540 --> 01:02:03.250
If everybody is holding
this portfolio M,

01:02:03.250 --> 01:02:04.990
that's the demand side, right?

01:02:04.990 --> 01:02:10.810
Everybody is demanding
M. On the supply side,

01:02:10.810 --> 01:02:16.460
I'm assuming that all stocks
that are being supplied

01:02:16.460 --> 01:02:17.780
are held.

01:02:17.780 --> 01:02:23.410
If all stocks that are being
supplied are held by somebody,

01:02:23.410 --> 01:02:27.490
but if everybody in the world
is holding the same portfolio

01:02:27.490 --> 01:02:31.044
M, when you aggregate
all of the demands.

01:02:31.044 --> 01:02:33.210
So I'm going to add up your
demand, and your demand,

01:02:33.210 --> 01:02:33.940
and your demand, and you're.

01:02:33.940 --> 01:02:34.910
We're going to go
through the class,

01:02:34.910 --> 01:02:36.451
and go through the
world, we're going

01:02:36.451 --> 01:02:38.070
to add up everybody's demand.

01:02:38.070 --> 01:02:43.690
In every single case, your
weights are identical.

01:02:43.690 --> 01:02:46.400
You're holding the
same portfolio M.

01:02:46.400 --> 01:02:49.200
So when I aggregate
the entire world,

01:02:49.200 --> 01:02:53.900
and I get the portfolio M,
what does it have to equal?

01:02:53.900 --> 01:02:57.740
It can only equal the sum total
of all assets in the world,

01:02:57.740 --> 01:02:58.370
right?

01:02:58.370 --> 01:03:01.800
Supply equals demand.

01:03:01.800 --> 01:03:06.120
And therefore, when I aggregate
all of your holdings of M

01:03:06.120 --> 01:03:09.780
into one big fat
M, that big fat M

01:03:09.780 --> 01:03:11.700
can only be equal to
one thing, which is

01:03:11.700 --> 01:03:14.530
all the equities in the world.

01:03:14.530 --> 01:03:18.231
And the weightings are just
simply their market caps,

01:03:18.231 --> 01:03:18.730
right?

01:03:18.730 --> 01:03:20.740
There's only so much
of General Motors.

01:03:20.740 --> 01:03:22.640
Take the entire
sum total of that,

01:03:22.640 --> 01:03:25.690
that's the global investment
in General Motors.

01:03:25.690 --> 01:03:27.670
And then you do that
for every single stock,

01:03:27.670 --> 01:03:33.260
and you divide that by the total
market capital of all stocks,

01:03:33.260 --> 01:03:37.240
you get the market portfolio, M.

01:03:37.240 --> 01:03:43.680
So this shockingly, simple,
but extraordinarily powerful

01:03:43.680 --> 01:03:46.670
result is due to Bill Sharpe.

01:03:46.670 --> 01:03:50.310
Harry Markowitz came up
with portfolio optimization.

01:03:50.310 --> 01:03:52.380
He applied mean
variance analysis

01:03:52.380 --> 01:03:55.094
to portfolio optimization
and argued that everybody

01:03:55.094 --> 01:03:56.010
has to be on the line.

01:03:56.010 --> 01:03:59.030
Bill Sharpe looked at
this and said, aha.

01:03:59.030 --> 01:04:00.619
If everybody's on
that line, that

01:04:00.619 --> 01:04:02.660
means that everybody's
going to be either holding

01:04:02.660 --> 01:04:06.050
M or T-Bills, or
both, and therefore,

01:04:06.050 --> 01:04:09.260
the only thing that
M could possibly be

01:04:09.260 --> 01:04:11.680
is the market portfolio.

01:04:11.680 --> 01:04:14.620
And now we have a proxy for the
market portfolio, the Russell

01:04:14.620 --> 01:04:15.700
2000.

01:04:15.700 --> 01:04:17.320
Or the S&amp;P 500.

01:04:17.320 --> 01:04:19.944
Both of those are very well
diversified stock that have

01:04:19.944 --> 01:04:21.610
lot-- they don't have
everything in it--

01:04:21.610 --> 01:04:24.950
but they have a lot of things in
it, that proxy for everything.

01:04:24.950 --> 01:04:29.770
The Russell 2000 has 2,000
stocks weighted by market cap.

01:04:29.770 --> 01:04:33.310
That's as close as you're going
to get to everything that you

01:04:33.310 --> 01:04:35.712
care about.

01:04:35.712 --> 01:04:37.920
So now, you'll see we're
benchmarking is coming from,

01:04:37.920 --> 01:04:40.290
but I'm going to get back
to that in more detail.

01:04:40.290 --> 01:04:47.380
So this equilibrium result
that says supply equals demand,

01:04:47.380 --> 01:04:52.030
identifies this portfolio
M. And what it says

01:04:52.030 --> 01:04:56.590
is that if everybody does this,
if everybody takes finance

01:04:56.590 --> 01:04:59.980
here and learns how
to do this, it's

01:04:59.980 --> 01:05:01.810
not going to kill the idea.

01:05:01.810 --> 01:05:05.320
It's going to lead to a
very well-defined portfolio

01:05:05.320 --> 01:05:09.445
M. Now, let me take
it one step farther,

01:05:09.445 --> 01:05:13.830
then I want to ask
you to ask questions.

01:05:13.830 --> 01:05:16.940
If I know what that
portfolio M is,

01:05:16.940 --> 01:05:20.945
then I've got an
equation for this line.

01:05:23.840 --> 01:05:28.040
I can write down a relationship
between the expected return

01:05:28.040 --> 01:05:31.280
and risk of a
portfolio on this line.

01:05:31.280 --> 01:05:33.190
And this is it.

01:05:33.190 --> 01:05:36.700
The expected rate of return
of an efficient portfolio,

01:05:36.700 --> 01:05:39.640
by efficient I mean a
portfolio that's on that line.

01:05:39.640 --> 01:05:43.100
Anything that's not on that
line, if it's below that line,

01:05:43.100 --> 01:05:45.470
it's inefficient, right?

01:05:45.470 --> 01:05:47.870
You're not getting as much
expected return per unit risk,

01:05:47.870 --> 01:05:50.780
and you're not reducing your
risk as much as you can,

01:05:50.780 --> 01:05:52.880
per unit of expected return.

01:05:52.880 --> 01:05:55.430
The expected return of
an efficient portfolio

01:05:55.430 --> 01:06:01.710
is equal to the risk-free
rate, plus the ratio

01:06:01.710 --> 01:06:05.610
of the standard deviation
of that portfolio, divided

01:06:05.610 --> 01:06:09.180
by the standard deviation
of the tangency portfolio,

01:06:09.180 --> 01:06:15.120
or the market, multiplied by
the excess return of the market

01:06:15.120 --> 01:06:15.780
portfolio.

01:06:20.360 --> 01:06:28.340
This result is a risk-reward
trade-off between risk

01:06:28.340 --> 01:06:30.610
and expected return.

01:06:30.610 --> 01:06:34.090
You see, what it says is really
something quite astounding.

01:06:34.090 --> 01:06:37.060
It's telling you that,
here's the risk-free rate.

01:06:37.060 --> 01:06:40.630
That's the base return
for your portfolio.

01:06:40.630 --> 01:06:42.520
And what this is
telling you is that what

01:06:42.520 --> 01:06:45.610
you should expect
for your portfolio

01:06:45.610 --> 01:06:50.650
is that base return,
plus something extra.

01:06:50.650 --> 01:06:55.800
And the extra is the
market's excess return,

01:06:55.800 --> 01:06:58.650
multiplied by a factor.

01:06:58.650 --> 01:07:00.930
And the factor is simply
how risky your portfolio

01:07:00.930 --> 01:07:03.990
is relative to the market.

01:07:03.990 --> 01:07:05.290
Let's do a simple example.

01:07:05.290 --> 01:07:09.960
Suppose that your portfolio
is the exact same risk

01:07:09.960 --> 01:07:11.912
as the market.

01:07:11.912 --> 01:07:13.370
Well, if that's
the case, then what

01:07:13.370 --> 01:07:15.216
is your expected rate of return?

01:07:15.216 --> 01:07:16.150
AUDIENCE: The market.

01:07:16.150 --> 01:07:17.274
ANDREW LO: It's the market.

01:07:17.274 --> 01:07:21.750
So it's the risk-free rate,
plus the market excess return,

01:07:21.750 --> 01:07:24.122
which, when you add it
together, is just the market.

01:07:24.122 --> 01:07:25.830
Suppose you're holding
a portfolio that's

01:07:25.830 --> 01:07:29.040
more risky than the market.

01:07:29.040 --> 01:07:30.900
Is your rate of
return greater or less

01:07:30.900 --> 01:07:32.070
than the rate of
return of the market?

01:07:32.070 --> 01:07:32.760
AUDIENCE: Greater.

01:07:32.760 --> 01:07:33.551
ANDREW LO: Greater.

01:07:33.551 --> 01:07:36.570
Suppose that your
portfolio has no risk.

01:07:36.570 --> 01:07:39.476
Suppose that sigma p is 0, then
what's your rate of return?

01:07:39.476 --> 01:07:40.350
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:07:40.350 --> 01:07:41.310
ANDREW LO: Exactly.

01:07:41.310 --> 01:07:42.270
Makes sense, right?

01:07:42.270 --> 01:07:44.370
This is very intuitive.

01:07:44.370 --> 01:07:48.000
What this tells us, now,
is that we can figure out

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:52.170
what the fair rate of return
is for an efficient portfolio.

01:07:52.170 --> 01:07:54.420
For any portfolio
on this line, I

01:07:54.420 --> 01:07:56.400
can tell you what my
fair rate of return is,

01:07:56.400 --> 01:07:58.620
and it's an objective measure.

01:07:58.620 --> 01:08:00.060
It's not just theory now.

01:08:00.060 --> 01:08:01.551
Now, I can go into
the marketplace,

01:08:01.551 --> 01:08:03.550
I can measure the expected
return of the market.

01:08:03.550 --> 01:08:05.050
You know what that
is, historically?

01:08:05.050 --> 01:08:06.945
Not including the
last few months.

01:08:06.945 --> 01:08:08.126
AUDIENCE: 7%.

01:08:08.126 --> 01:08:09.750
ANDREW LO: It's about
7%, historically.

01:08:09.750 --> 01:08:12.180
Over the last 100
years, 7%, the expected

01:08:12.180 --> 01:08:14.730
rate of return of the market.

01:08:14.730 --> 01:08:16.316
Sorry, the expected
risk premium,

01:08:16.316 --> 01:08:17.399
the excess rate of return.

01:08:17.399 --> 01:08:18.414
About 7%.

01:08:18.414 --> 01:08:20.080
What about the
volatility of the market?

01:08:20.080 --> 01:08:22.229
It's been about
15% historically.

01:08:22.229 --> 01:08:24.899
So according to
this relationship,

01:08:24.899 --> 01:08:26.910
I've already figured
out what this number is.

01:08:26.910 --> 01:08:28.036
It's like 7%.

01:08:28.036 --> 01:08:29.910
I've already figured
out what this number is.

01:08:29.910 --> 01:08:31.410
It's like 15%.

01:08:31.410 --> 01:08:34.890
So now, you should be able
to get a benchmark for what

01:08:34.890 --> 01:08:38.670
to expect when you've got
a particular level of risk

01:08:38.670 --> 01:08:41.069
in an efficient portfolio.

01:08:41.069 --> 01:08:42.510
You've got all the ingredients.

01:08:42.510 --> 01:08:43.593
What about risk-free rate?

01:08:43.593 --> 01:08:45.450
Well, it depends on
what risk-free rate,

01:08:45.450 --> 01:08:47.460
but let's talk about
over a one year period.

01:08:47.460 --> 01:08:48.960
Right now we're
looking at somewhere

01:08:48.960 --> 01:08:52.109
between, I don't
know, 1%, 2%, 3%,

01:08:52.109 --> 01:08:55.290
depending on what day of
the week you're looking at.

01:08:55.290 --> 01:08:58.938
So one year T-Bill rate
is about 1% or so, yeah?

01:08:58.938 --> 01:09:00.688
AUDIENCE: I think it
was the last class we

01:09:00.688 --> 01:09:02.064
talked about unsystematic risk.

01:09:02.064 --> 01:09:02.689
ANDREW LO: Yes.

01:09:02.689 --> 01:09:06.870
AUDIENCE: Is that defined
by [INAUDIBLE] in this case?

01:09:06.870 --> 01:09:08.580
ANDREW LO: No, the
unsystematic risk

01:09:08.580 --> 01:09:10.890
is risk that is not
measured by sigma p,

01:09:10.890 --> 01:09:12.960
so we're going to
come back to that.

01:09:12.960 --> 01:09:14.729
Let me hold off on
that for now, because I

01:09:14.729 --> 01:09:16.930
want to come back to it after
I finish developing this.

01:09:16.930 --> 01:09:18.626
There's going to be
a connection between

01:09:18.626 --> 01:09:20.250
systematic and
unsystematic risk that's

01:09:20.250 --> 01:09:22.990
going to come right out
of this relationship.

01:09:22.990 --> 01:09:23.490
Yeah, Brian?

01:09:23.490 --> 01:09:28.310
AUDIENCE: So if you take
the S&amp;P 500 as M here,

01:09:28.310 --> 01:09:31.640
the market portfolio, and the
capitalization is the weight,

01:09:31.640 --> 01:09:34.855
so you've got non-zero weights
for all the different stocks

01:09:34.855 --> 01:09:35.430
there.

01:09:35.430 --> 01:09:38.760
Does that imply that there's
no stocks in the S&amp;P 500

01:09:38.760 --> 01:09:41.160
that are Southeast
of any others?

01:09:41.160 --> 01:09:42.819
ANDREW LO: No, no,
there could be.

01:09:42.819 --> 01:09:43.630
AUDIENCE: Why would
you have them,

01:09:43.630 --> 01:09:45.671
because we said those are
strictly non-preferred?

01:09:45.671 --> 01:09:47.910
ANDREW LO: Well, that's
if you're looking

01:09:47.910 --> 01:09:49.800
at a pairwise comparison.

01:09:49.800 --> 01:09:52.200
If, now, you're trying to
create an entire collection

01:09:52.200 --> 01:09:53.850
of these portfolios
of securities,

01:09:53.850 --> 01:09:55.129
that's a different story.

01:09:55.129 --> 01:09:57.420
That's why I answered in
response to Justin's question.

01:09:57.420 --> 01:09:59.850
Justin said, why not
just trade off those two?

01:09:59.850 --> 01:10:00.380
Why not?

01:10:00.380 --> 01:10:03.090
It's because you can do far
better by using all of them

01:10:03.090 --> 01:10:04.290
in this way.

01:10:04.290 --> 01:10:07.200
You see, by looking at pairwise,
you can no doubt do better.

01:10:07.200 --> 01:10:10.644
But if I use all of them,
I get this entire line.

01:10:10.644 --> 01:10:12.060
And you can't get
that entire line

01:10:12.060 --> 01:10:13.780
just from looking at
two of these stocks,

01:10:13.780 --> 01:10:14.580
you need all of them.

01:10:14.580 --> 01:10:16.250
AUDIENCE: So in this
portfolio of three,

01:10:16.250 --> 01:10:18.520
if you kick GM over to
the right a little bit,

01:10:18.520 --> 01:10:20.530
and made it strictly
non-preferred to IBM,

01:10:20.530 --> 01:10:24.280
then you still might
have a positive portfolio

01:10:24.280 --> 01:10:25.560
weight on GM?

01:10:25.560 --> 01:10:27.360
ANDREW LO: You might,
but more likely,

01:10:27.360 --> 01:10:28.917
it'll be a negative
portfolio weight.

01:10:28.917 --> 01:10:30.750
It'll be negative, and
you'll be shorting it

01:10:30.750 --> 01:10:32.750
somewhere along the line here.

01:10:32.750 --> 01:10:36.930
However, the tangency
portfolio, by assumption,

01:10:36.930 --> 01:10:41.490
if it's the market portfolio,
cannot have negative weights.

01:10:41.490 --> 01:10:45.570
And so there, what will happen,
is that all of the stocks

01:10:45.570 --> 01:10:47.580
will change in
their relationship

01:10:47.580 --> 01:10:50.230
based upon various different
kinds of equilibrium,

01:10:50.230 --> 01:10:52.440
so that you won't get into
a lot of those situations

01:10:52.440 --> 01:10:55.300
where you're going to be
shorting these negative stocks.

01:10:55.300 --> 01:10:55.800
Yeah?

01:10:55.800 --> 01:10:59.132
AUDIENCE: So basically,
according to the Sharpe theory,

01:10:59.132 --> 01:11:04.380
every stock that the
market, the capital is not 0

01:11:04.380 --> 01:11:06.500
is worth holding
in some portfolio?

01:11:06.500 --> 01:11:07.500
ANDREW LO: That's right.

01:11:07.500 --> 01:11:09.030
AUDIENCE: Diversifying
your portfolio.

01:11:09.030 --> 01:11:10.030
ANDREW LO: That's right.

01:11:10.030 --> 01:11:12.990
Every stock has some
benefit in adding

01:11:12.990 --> 01:11:15.570
to this particular
risk-reward trade-off,

01:11:15.570 --> 01:11:19.660
and the sum total benefit
is summarized by this line.

01:11:19.660 --> 01:11:20.910
That's the ultimate objective.

01:11:20.910 --> 01:11:23.390
AUDIENCE: If I don't hold a
specific stock in the market

01:11:23.390 --> 01:11:26.502
and I gain a
diversification [INAUDIBLE]?

01:11:26.502 --> 01:11:27.210
ANDREW LO: Sorry?

01:11:27.210 --> 01:11:29.864
If you hold a specific stock?

01:11:29.864 --> 01:11:31.530
AUDIENCE: If I don't
hold it, because it

01:11:31.530 --> 01:11:32.510
has market [INAUDIBLE].

01:11:32.510 --> 01:11:34.370
ANDREW LO: Oh, if
you put 0 weight.

01:11:34.370 --> 01:11:35.640
Yes.

01:11:35.640 --> 01:11:38.730
What Sharpe would argue,
based upon this theory,

01:11:38.730 --> 01:11:41.190
is that you want to
hold as many stocks

01:11:41.190 --> 01:11:43.770
as you can to get the
most diversification.

01:11:43.770 --> 01:11:45.210
Now, that's the theory.

01:11:45.210 --> 01:11:49.410
In practice, it may well
be that the benefits do not

01:11:49.410 --> 01:11:51.960
outweigh the costs, because
when you hold multiple stocks,

01:11:51.960 --> 01:11:54.900
you have to manage them,
and so it may cost more.

01:11:54.900 --> 01:11:57.330
So a mutual fund
that has 3,000 stocks

01:11:57.330 --> 01:12:01.080
may have a higher expense ratio
than a mutual fund with 500.

01:12:01.080 --> 01:12:01.800
It may not.

01:12:01.800 --> 01:12:04.500
Nowadays, actually, the
technology is so good that

01:12:04.500 --> 01:12:05.580
probably it doesn't.

01:12:05.580 --> 01:12:08.250
But 15 years ago,
that was not true.

01:12:08.250 --> 01:12:10.140
But apart from the
transactions cost,

01:12:10.140 --> 01:12:13.420
the theory suggests
more is better.

01:12:13.420 --> 01:12:16.124
Because it will always give
you more opportunities, and it

01:12:16.124 --> 01:12:18.540
can never hurt you because you
could always put a 0 weight

01:12:18.540 --> 01:12:19.831
on them if you don't like them.

01:12:22.330 --> 01:12:30.040
Now, it turns out that this is
a trade-off between the expected

01:12:30.040 --> 01:12:35.820
return of an
efficient portfolio,

01:12:35.820 --> 01:12:37.860
and the risk of that portfolio.

01:12:37.860 --> 01:12:41.460
In other words,
this applies only

01:12:41.460 --> 01:12:45.100
to portfolios on
that tangency line.

01:12:45.100 --> 01:12:48.040
What if you want to know what
the expected rate of return

01:12:48.040 --> 01:12:51.120
is for Wal-Mart?

01:12:51.120 --> 01:12:54.510
We just said that
no individual stock

01:12:54.510 --> 01:12:58.170
is going to be likely to be
on that efficient frontier.

01:12:58.170 --> 01:13:00.690
And therefore, no
individual stock

01:13:00.690 --> 01:13:03.016
is likely to be on this line.

01:13:03.016 --> 01:13:04.890
So this is great if what
you're talking about

01:13:04.890 --> 01:13:07.230
is investing in
efficient portfolios,

01:13:07.230 --> 01:13:09.500
but how does that help the
corporate financial officer

01:13:09.500 --> 01:13:11.041
that's trying to
figure out how to do

01:13:11.041 --> 01:13:13.650
capital budgeting for a
particular pharmaceutical

01:13:13.650 --> 01:13:15.399
project?

01:13:15.399 --> 01:13:16.440
It turns out, it doesn't.

01:13:16.440 --> 01:13:17.106
It doesn't help.

01:13:17.106 --> 01:13:19.770
This doesn't answer
that question.

01:13:19.770 --> 01:13:24.630
It turns out, you need to have
an additional piece of theory

01:13:24.630 --> 01:13:28.590
that allows you to derive
the same results, not

01:13:28.590 --> 01:13:33.370
just for the efficient
portfolios here,

01:13:33.370 --> 01:13:35.590
but for any portfolio.

01:13:35.590 --> 01:13:37.780
And this is another
innovation of Bill Sharpe.

01:13:37.780 --> 01:13:40.190
This is actually why Bill
Sharpe won the Nobel Prize.

01:13:40.190 --> 01:13:42.250
It was not for this
little picture here,

01:13:42.250 --> 01:13:45.310
but it was for this
equation right here.

01:13:45.310 --> 01:13:50.110
What Bill Sharpe discovered is
after computing the equilibrium

01:13:50.110 --> 01:13:53.810
relationships among various
different securities,

01:13:53.810 --> 01:13:58.670
he's demonstrated that there
has to be a linear relationship

01:13:58.670 --> 01:14:05.230
between any stock's expected
return and the market risk

01:14:05.230 --> 01:14:06.550
premium.

01:14:06.550 --> 01:14:09.370
Just like here, where you've
got the risk-free rate,

01:14:09.370 --> 01:14:11.800
plus some extra premium.

01:14:11.800 --> 01:14:14.620
So this is the premium,
the second term.

01:14:14.620 --> 01:14:18.790
But what Bill Sharpe showed was
that if this portfolio is not

01:14:18.790 --> 01:14:24.120
an efficient portfolio,
if it's not on that line,

01:14:24.120 --> 01:14:27.810
the linear relationship
still holds.

01:14:27.810 --> 01:14:31.080
But it turns out that this
particular multiplier is

01:14:31.080 --> 01:14:34.210
no longer the right one to use.

01:14:34.210 --> 01:14:39.300
It turns out that the right
parameter to plug in there,

01:14:39.300 --> 01:14:42.240
is something called beta.

01:14:42.240 --> 01:14:44.440
Now, you've heard all
about beta, I'm sure.

01:14:44.440 --> 01:14:47.500
But now, I'm telling you
exactly what beta is.

01:14:47.500 --> 01:14:51.010
Beta is the multiplier
that is defined

01:14:51.010 --> 01:14:54.640
by the covariance between
the return on the market

01:14:54.640 --> 01:14:57.760
and the return on the
individual asset, divided

01:14:57.760 --> 01:15:00.220
by the variance of
that market return.

01:15:03.860 --> 01:15:08.780
If the portfolio happens to
be on that efficient frontier,

01:15:08.780 --> 01:15:13.040
then this beta reduces
to this previous measure.

01:15:13.040 --> 01:15:17.090
So this is a special case of
the more general relationship

01:15:17.090 --> 01:15:20.560
where beta is used
as the multiplier.

01:15:20.560 --> 01:15:21.960
So let me repeat what beta is.

01:15:21.960 --> 01:15:26.250
Beta is the ratio of the
covariance between the return

01:15:26.250 --> 01:15:28.860
on the particular asset or
portfolio, that may or may not

01:15:28.860 --> 01:15:33.350
be efficient, it's any
asset, with the return

01:15:33.350 --> 01:15:34.980
on the market portfolio.

01:15:34.980 --> 01:15:39.710
So this numerator is a
measure of the covariability

01:15:39.710 --> 01:15:42.200
between the particular
asset that you're

01:15:42.200 --> 01:15:45.410
trying to measure the
expected return of,

01:15:45.410 --> 01:15:48.890
and that tangency
portfolio, divided

01:15:48.890 --> 01:15:53.390
by the variance of that
tangency portfolio.

01:15:56.010 --> 01:16:00.960
Beta, it turns out, is
the right measure of risk,

01:16:00.960 --> 01:16:05.190
in the sense that it is the
beta that determines what

01:16:05.190 --> 01:16:09.480
the multiplier is going to be on
the market risk premium, which

01:16:09.480 --> 01:16:13.290
is to be added to your asset's
expected rate of return,

01:16:13.290 --> 01:16:15.810
above and beyond
the risk-free rate.

01:16:15.810 --> 01:16:19.920
That's how the cost of capital
is determined for your asset.

01:16:24.030 --> 01:16:27.420
So I think you all saw
how I derived this,

01:16:27.420 --> 01:16:29.070
but I didn't derive this.

01:16:29.070 --> 01:16:30.600
I'm just telling
you this is really

01:16:30.600 --> 01:16:35.700
where Sharpe's ideas became
extraordinarily compelling.

01:16:35.700 --> 01:16:37.800
And in order to
understand how to derive

01:16:37.800 --> 01:16:41.017
that, I'm going to refer
you to 433, because

01:16:41.017 --> 01:16:42.600
in that investment's
course, we really

01:16:42.600 --> 01:16:46.082
delve into the underpinnings
of that kind of calculation.

01:16:46.082 --> 01:16:47.540
It's a little bit
more involved, it

01:16:47.540 --> 01:16:49.470
involves some matrix algebra.

01:16:49.470 --> 01:16:52.502
But it's not terribly
difficult or challenging,

01:16:52.502 --> 01:16:54.960
and certainly be happy to give
you references if any of you

01:16:54.960 --> 01:16:55.710
are interested.

01:16:55.710 --> 01:16:59.370
I believe it's in
Brealey, Myers, and Allen.

01:16:59.370 --> 01:17:01.380
But the bottom line
is that this gives you

01:17:01.380 --> 01:17:04.490
an extraordinarily
important conclusion now

01:17:04.490 --> 01:17:09.930
to the several weeks that we've
been working towards this goal.

01:17:09.930 --> 01:17:14.100
Which is now, finally,
after eight or nine weeks,

01:17:14.100 --> 01:17:17.850
I can tell you how to come up
with the appropriate discount

01:17:17.850 --> 01:17:21.120
rate for various
NPV calculations.

01:17:21.120 --> 01:17:23.640
The answer is the
expected rate of return,

01:17:23.640 --> 01:17:26.940
the appropriate
fair rate of return,

01:17:26.940 --> 01:17:30.300
or the market equilibrium
rate of return,

01:17:30.300 --> 01:17:33.960
is simply given by the beta
of that security, multiplied

01:17:33.960 --> 01:17:39.140
by the expected excess return
on the market portfolio.

01:17:39.140 --> 01:17:41.729
So now, this has a lot
of assumptions, granted.

01:17:41.729 --> 01:17:43.520
We're going to talk
about those assumptions

01:17:43.520 --> 01:17:46.430
over the next
couple of lectures.

01:17:46.430 --> 01:17:50.740
But what we've done today
is move the theory forward

01:17:50.740 --> 01:17:55.030
by quite a bit, because we've
identified a particular method

01:17:55.030 --> 01:17:58.150
for coming up with the
appropriate cost of capital

01:17:58.150 --> 01:17:59.440
as a function of the risk.

01:17:59.440 --> 01:18:03.340
Where the risk is measured,
not by volatility anymore,

01:18:03.340 --> 01:18:09.710
but by the covariance between an
asset and the market portfolio.

01:18:09.710 --> 01:18:11.960
And next time, I'm
going to try to give you

01:18:11.960 --> 01:18:14.300
some intuition for
why this should be,

01:18:14.300 --> 01:18:20.120
why this makes sense, and why,
in a mean variance efficient

01:18:20.120 --> 01:18:23.840
set of portfolios, why it
reduces to something that we

01:18:23.840 --> 01:18:24.650
know and love.

01:18:27.930 --> 01:18:30.670
Any questions?

01:18:30.670 --> 01:18:31.170
OK.

01:18:31.170 --> 01:18:34.010
I'll stop here, and I'll
see you on Wednesday.

